Part I


First, let’s read in the LondonGangNet network. This is stored as an .rds document in the data folder on the SNA Textbook site. We will use the readRDS() function, with the file path, to load the file. Since we are calling a url, we need to use the url() function as well.

Finally, we need to make sure the sna and network packages are loaded, using library(), so that R recognizes the LondonGangNet object as one of class network.


# load the libraries we need
library( sna )
library( network )

# define the path location for the file
loc <- "https://github.com/jacobtnyoung/sna-textbook/raw/main/data/data-london-gang-net.rds"
LondonGangNet <- readRDS( url(loc ) )

# look at the network
LondonGangNet
##  Network attributes:
##   vertices = 54 
##   directed = FALSE 
##   hyper = FALSE 
##   loops = FALSE 
##   multiple = FALSE 
##   bipartite = FALSE 
##   total edges= 315 
##     missing edges= 0 
##     non-missing edges= 315 
## 
##  Vertex attribute names: 
##     Age Arrests Birthplace Convictions Music Prison Ranking Residence vertex.names 
## 
## No edge attributes


1. Calculate and report the degree, closeness, and betweenness centrality scores for each actor.


# use the degree() function in the sna package
deg.gang <- degree( 
  LondonGangNet,
  gmode = "graph", 
  cmode = "degree"
  )

Recall that the closeness() function reports the standardized closeness centrality by default. If we want the unstandardized closeness, we can just divide the result returned by closeness() by g-1.

# set the number of nodes in the network
g <- dim( as.matrix( LondonGangNet ) )[1]

# raw closeness centrality
close.gang <- closeness( LondonGangNet, gmode="graph" ) / ( g - 1 )

# raw betweenness centrality
btwn.gang <- betweenness( 
  LondonGangNet, 
  gmode="graph" 
  )
# create a data frame that shows the values for each individual
cent.dat <- data.frame(
  degree = deg.gang,
  closeness = close.gang,
  betweenness = btwn.gang
)

# show the first 25 cases
head( cent.dat, 25 )


2. Calculate and report the standardized degree, closeness, and betweenness centrality scores for each actor.

# standardized score is deg / g-1 where g is the number of nodes
s.deg.gang <- deg.gang / ( g - 1 )

# standardized closeness is the score reported by default
s.close.gang <- closeness( LondonGangNet, gmode="graph" )

# standardized betweenness is the betweenness / ( ( ( g-1 ) * ( g-2 ) ) / 2 )
s.btwn.gang <- btwn.gang / ( ( ( g-1 ) * ( g-2 ) ) / 2 )
# create a data frame that shows the values for each individual
s.cent.dat <- data.frame(
  s.degree = s.deg.gang,
  s.closeness = s.close.gang,
  s.betweenness = s.btwn.gang
)

# show the last 25 cases
tail( s.cent.dat, 25 )


3. Calculate and report the mean (unstandardized) degree, closeness, and betweenness centrality scores.

# use the mean() function to calculate the means
mean.deg.gang   <- mean( deg.gang )
mean.close.gang <- mean( close.gang )
mean.btwn.gang  <- mean( btwn.gang )

# create a table that is easy to read
cent.tab <- data.frame( 
  deg = round( mean.deg.gang, 2 ),
  close = round( mean.close.gang, 2 ),
  between = round( mean.btwn.gang, 2 )
  )

# print the table
cent.tab


4. Interpret each mean centrality score.

The mean degree centrality score is 11.67 meaning that the average node has 11.67 edges incident on them. The mean closeness centrality score is 0.01, meaning that the average node is very close to all other nodes in the network. Finally, the mean betweenness centrality score is 27.93, meaning that the average node sits on 27.93 paths between i and j.


5. Calculate the graph centralization for degree, closeness, and betweenness centrality.

dcent.gang <- centralization( LondonGangNet, degree, mode="graph", cmode="degree" )
ccent.gang <- centralization( LondonGangNet, closeness, mode="graph" )
bcent.gang <- centralization( LondonGangNet, betweenness, mode="graph" )

# create a table that is easy to read
centralization.tab <- data.frame( 
  deg = round( dcent.gang, 2 ),
  close = round( ccent.gang, 2 ),
  between = round( bcent.gang, 2 )
  )

# print the table
centralization.tab


6. Interpret each graph centralization score.

The degree centralization score is0.26 and the closeness centralization score is 0.31. Both are somewhat close to zero indicating that the nodes do not differ substantially in terms of their scores.

The betweenness centralization score is very close to zero, at 0.09 meaning that there is very little variation between nodes in terms of their scores.


7. Plot the network three times using the gplot() function where each plot sizes the nodes by the centrality score (i.e. a plot for degree centrality, a plot for closeness centrality, and a plot for betweenness centrality).

We can use a for loop to build a series of plots. Let’s do the same here. We will incorporate the rescale() function to appropriately size the nodes.

# create the rescale function
rescale <- function( nchar, low, high ){
  min_d <- min( nchar )
  max_d <- max( nchar )
  rscl  <- ( ( high - low )*( nchar - min_d ) ) / ( max_d - min_d ) + low
  rscl
}

# create the inputs for the loop
titles  <- c( "Degree", "Closeness", "Betweenness")
cols    <- c( "#5c1233", "#0c7091", "#949c7b" )
v.sizes <- cbind( deg.gang, close.gang, btwn.gang )

# change the margins using the mar= argument
# change the number of plots using the mfrow= argument
par( 
  mfrow=c( 2,2 ),
  mar=c( 0.1, 0.5, 1, 0.1 ) 
  )

for( i in 1:3 ){
  
  # set the seed
  set.seed( 507 )

  # render the plot
  gplot( 
  LondonGangNet,
  gmode = "graph",
  label.cex = 0.6,
  vertex.col = cols[i],
  vertex.cex = rescale( v.sizes[,i], 0.5, 1.5 ),
  main = titles[i]
  )

}


8. Examine the plots. Describe how the differences you noted between the centrality measures above are seen in the plots.

The plots show that all three measures describe similar aspects of the network. Mainly, that there are core nodes (larger) and peripheral nodes (smaller). And, that there is much overlap in the network.



Part II


First, let’s read in the CocaineDealingNet network. This is stored as an .rds document in the data folder on the SNA Textbook site. We will use the readRDS() function, with the file path, to load the file. Since we are calling a url, we need to use the url() function as well.

Above, we needed to make sure the sna and network packages were loaded, but we loaded them above so we do not need to repeat the step here.


# define the path location for the file
loc2 <- "https://github.com/jacobtnyoung/sna-textbook/raw/main/data/data-cocaine-dealing-net.rds"
CocaineDealingNet <- readRDS( url(loc2 ) )

# look at the network
CocaineDealingNet
##  Network attributes:
##   vertices = 28 
##   directed = TRUE 
##   hyper = FALSE 
##   loops = FALSE

1. Calculate and report the indegree, outdegree, closeness, and betweenness centrality scores for each actor.

# use the degree() function in the sna package.
ideg.coc <- degree( 
  CocaineDealingNet,
  gmode = "digraph", # note the change to a directed graph  
  cmode = "indegree" # ask for the indegree
  )

odeg.coc <- degree( 
  CocaineDealingNet,
  gmode = "digraph",  # note the change to a directed graph
  cmode = "outdegree" # toggle to return the outdegree
  )


Now let’s calculate the closeness and betweenness scores. Again, recall that the closeness() function reports the standardized closeness centrality by default. If we want the unstandardized closeness, we can just divide the result returned by closeness() by g. Note, that since the graph is directed, we divide by g, not g-1.

# set the number of nodes in the network
g <- dim( as.matrix( CocaineDealingNet ) )[1]

# raw closeness centrality
close.coc <- closeness( CocaineDealingNet, gmode="digraph" ) / g 

# raw betweenness centrality
btwn.coc <- betweenness( 
  CocaineDealingNet, 
  gmode="digraph" 
  )
# create a data frame that shows the values for each individual
cent.dat <- data.frame(
  idegree = ideg.coc,
  odegree = odeg.coc,
  closeness = close.coc,
  betweenness = btwn.coc
)

# show the first 25 cases
head( cent.dat, 25 )


2. Calculate and report the standardized indegree, outdegree, closeness, and betweenness centrality scores for each actor.

# standardized score is deg / g-1 where g is the number of nodes
s.ideg.coc <- ideg.coc / ( g - 1 )
s.odeg.coc <- odeg.coc / ( g - 1 )

# standardized closeness is the score reported by default
s.close.coc <- closeness( CocaineDealingNet, gmode="digraph" )

# standardized betweenness is the betweenness / ( ( ( g-1 ) * ( g-2 ) ) / 2 )
s.btwn.coc <- btwn.coc / ( ( ( g-1 ) * ( g-2 ) ) / 2 )
# create a data frame that shows the values for each individual
s.cent.dat <- data.frame(
  s.idegree = s.ideg.coc,
  s.odegree = s.odeg.coc,
  s.closeness = s.close.coc,
  s.betweenness = s.btwn.coc
)

# show the last 25 cases
tail( s.cent.dat, 25 )


3. Calculate the mean (unstandardized) indegree, outdegree, closeness, and betweenness centrality score.

# use the mean() function to calculate the means
mean.ideg.coc  <- mean( ideg.coc )
mean.odeg.coc  <- mean( odeg.coc )
mean.close.coc <- mean( close.coc )
mean.btwn.coc  <- mean( btwn.coc )

# create a table that is easy to read
cent.tab <- data.frame( 
  ideg = round( mean.ideg.coc, 2 ),
  odeg = round( mean.odeg.coc, 2 ),
  close = round( mean.close.coc, 2 ),
  between = round( mean.btwn.coc, 2 )
  )

# print the table
cent.tab


4. Interpret each mean centrality score.

The mean indegree centrality score is 1.43 meaning that the average node receives 1.43 ties. The mean outdegree centrality score is equal, at 1.43. The mean closeness centrality score is 0, meaning that the average node is not close to the other nodes in the network. Finally, the mean betweenness centrality score is 0.46, meaning that the average node sits on 0.46 paths between i and j.


5. Calculate the graph centralization for indegree, outdegree, closeness, and betweenness centrality.

# calculate the centralization scores
icent.coc <- centralization( CocaineDealingNet, degree,      mode="digraph", cmode="indegree" )
ocent.coc <- centralization( CocaineDealingNet, degree,      mode="digraph", cmode="outdegree" )
ccent.coc <- centralization( CocaineDealingNet, closeness,   mode="digraph" )
bcent.coc <- centralization( CocaineDealingNet, betweenness, mode="digraph" )

# create a table that is easy to read
centralization.tab <- data.frame( 
  ideg = round( icent.coc, 2 ),
  odeg = round( ocent.coc, 2 ),
  close = round( ccent.coc, 2 ),
  between = round( bcent.coc, 2 )
  )

# print the table
centralization.tab


6. Interpret each graph centralization score.

The indegree centralization score is very close to 0, at 0.06 meaning that most nodes are very similar in their ties received.

The outdegree centralization score is very close to 1, at 0.87 meaning that a single node is mainly responsible for sending most of the ties.

The closeness centralization score is very close to 1, at 0.93 meaning that a single node has a very large closeness centrality score and the other nodes have very small closeness centrality scores.

The betweenness centralization score is very close to zero, at 0.01 meaning that the nodes do not differ substantially in terms of their betweenness.


7. Plot the network four times using the gplot() function where each plot sizes the nodes by the centrality score (i.e. a plot for indegree centrality, a plot for outdegree centrality, a plot for closeness centrality, and a plot for betweenness centrality).


# create the rescale function
rescale <- function( nchar, low, high ){
  min_d <- min( nchar )
  max_d <- max( nchar )
  rscl  <- ( ( high - low )*( nchar - min_d ) ) / ( max_d - min_d ) + low
  rscl
}

# create the inputs for the loop
titles  <- c( "Indegree", "Outdegree", "Closeness", "Betweenness")
cols    <- c( "#61476e", "#394d41", "#633b3d", "#bac22d" )
v.sizes <- cbind( ideg.coc, odeg.coc, close.coc, btwn.coc )

# change the margins using the mar= argument
# change the number of plots using the mfrow= argument
par( 
  mfrow=c( 2,2 ),
  mar=c( 0.1, 0.5, 1, 0.1 ) 
  )

for( i in 1:4 ){
  
  # set the seed
  set.seed( 507 )

  # render the plot
  gplot( 
  CocaineDealingNet,
  gmode = "digraph",
  label.cex = 0.6,
  arrowhead.cex = 0.3,
  vertex.col = cols[i],
  vertex.cex = rescale( v.sizes[,i], 0.5, 1.5 ),
  main = titles[i]
  )

}


8. Examine the plots. Describe how the differences you noted between the centrality measures above are seen in the plots.

The plots really help visualize the differences in the centrality measures discussed above. For example, the center node has the highest closeness score because all the other nodes are “far” from each other due to the directional nature of the plot. This is also the case for the outdegree centrality score. The indegree centrality and betweenness centrality scores point to different actors in the network as “central”. This is mainly a consequence of the directional nature of the network.
